\begin_layout Exercise
Zero price effect.
 You read,
 for problem set 2,
 the following chapter from Predictabily Irrational from Dan Ariely:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
\begin_inset CommandInset href
LatexCommand href
target "http://christophe.heintz.free.fr/bgt/Ariely-Predicably-Irrational-Ch3.pdf "
literal "false"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Exercise
from pages 55-60.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition*
Zero Price Effect.
 The zero price effect is an experimental finding that shows that even when relative price differences are the same among two goods,
 choices change significantly when one of the prices is zero.
 In particular,
 consumers may choose one good when both prices are positive,
 to a free good while keeping the price difference the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More formally,
 let there be two items 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in X$
\end_inset

,
 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is a Lindt truffle and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is a Hershey Kiss.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In the first experiment,
 the price of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 was 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}^{1}=15$
\end_inset

 cents per unit and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}^{1}=1$
\end_inset

 cent per unit.
 In that case most consumers chose 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Then in the second experiment the prices where changed,
 keeping the price difference constant,
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}^{2}=14$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}^{2}=0$
\end_inset

.
 In that case,
 most consumer chose 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
Incompatibility of the Zero Price Effect with Rationality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the tools of revealed preferences to answer the question of whether this experimental findings are consistent with rationality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In particular,
 note that in experiment 1,
 given that a subject bought 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}^{1}=15$
\end_inset

,
 she could have buy 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 at 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}^{1}=1$
\end_inset

.
 That means that 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is revealed preferred to 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 strictly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
In experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

,
 given the experiment 1,
 the subject can afford both the 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 because both are cheaper,
 moreover the price difference is the same as in experiment 1,
 however 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is chosen over 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This means that the subject cannot be rational.
 We can add a bit more detail to the model,
 consider 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)=g(a)-c(a)$
\end_inset

 where the utility of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 is the benefit of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 versus the cost of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

,
 for simplicity let 
\begin_inset Formula $c(a)=p_{a}$
\end_inset

.
 In experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)=g(a)-15$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)=g(b)-1$
\end_inset

,
 then when the subject chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

,
 we conclude that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)>u(b)$
\end_inset

 which implies 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)-g(b)\geq14$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then in experiment 
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

,
 we get that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)=g(a)-14$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u(b)=g(b)-0$
\end_inset

,
 notice that the main idea behind a rational consumer is that preferences remain stable,
 so the benefits are the same.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then it must be that 
\begin_inset Formula $u(a)>u(b)$
\end_inset

 because 
\begin_inset Formula $g(a)-g(b)\geq14$
\end_inset

 by the first experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection*
Your Task:
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
You are required to provide a 
\series bold
decision algorithm 
\series default
that accommodates/explains the zero price effect described above.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
You should use approximately 1 page for this.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Describe the choice algorith in words,
 or diagrams,
 explaining step-by-step how the consumer will choose,
 when given two alternatives 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a,b\}$
\end_inset

 and two prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{a}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}$
\end_inset

 (same environment that in the experiment).
 (If you feel comfortable,
 
\series bold
also
\series default
,
 describing your model in mathematical terms,
 this is OK with me).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Use your decision algorithm to accomodate and explain the zero price effect.
 Explain in one paragraph,
 what is the key feature of your model,
 that is different from the standard rational model that allows you to explain the zero price effect.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We consider a model of inattention to prices 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}^{s}=p_{j}^{m}(p_{j}^{d})^{1-m}$
\end_inset

,
 we let 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{j}^{d}=1$
\end_inset

 and we have the following,
 for the first experiment 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(a)-15^{m}>g(b)-1^{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the second experiment:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(a)-14^{m}<g(b)-0^{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Putting things together:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(a)-15^{m}+1^{m}>g(b)>g(a)-14^{m}
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
15^{m}-1^{m}<14^{m}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It turns out that for 
\begin_inset Formula $m<1$
\end_inset

 the previous inequality works,
 let 
\begin_inset Formula $m=\frac{1}{2}$
\end_inset

 and we verify that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
g(a)=3.3,g(b)=0,
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
verify the inequalities from the experiment.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\end_layout

